         <abstract>
            <p>Twice in eight years this country has teetered on the brink of financial panic. With the many unseen changes taking place in financial institutions, we must increase, rather than decrease, the flexibility of our system. The plea is here made that before the next crisis--that is, before the decision is again made to tighten money at any cost--some provision should be made to assure the liquidity of the banking system. Banks must be assured of a source of liquidity during a crisis not of their making. The time to cope with the problem is now. The Fed must be made to provide adequate funds in a financial crisis.</p>
          </abstract>
